li.p:
Draw a graph of the function
f(x) = \begin{cases} 1, \amp \ \text{if}\ 0 \lt x \lt 1 \\ 4, \amp \ \text{if}\ 2 \lt x \lt 3. \end{cases}
Then draw a graph of an antiderivative of f(x); call it F(x). Now draw a graph of another antiderivative of f(x) that is not of the form F(x)+C for any single constant C. Finally, write down a formula for the general antiderivative of f.

Repeat part (b) for the function

  h(x) =
  \begin{cases}
  2, \amp \ \text{if}\ x \neq -1 \\
  \text{undefined}, \amp \ \text{if}\ x=-1.
  \end{cases}

The two pieces can be shifted up or down by different constants. The general antiderivative is
F(x) = \begin{cases} x + C_1, \amp \ \text{if}\ 0 \lt x \lt 1 \\ 4x + C_2, \amp \ \text{if}\ 2 \lt x \lt 3. \end{cases}
for real constants C_1 and C_2.

The two pieces can be shifted up or down by different constants, since taking the derivative at a point in one interval will only use values of the function in that interval. The general antiderivative is
F(x) = \begin{cases} x + C_1, \amp \ \text{if}\ 0 \lt x \lt 1 \\ 4x + C_2, \amp \ \text{if}\ 2 \lt x \lt 3. \end{cases}
for real constants C_1 and C_2.
